							<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Hello all, long time lurker of eqdiva.com/concerthall boards and 3.5 year bard from eq1.
<br />
I recognize a few names here (steppy/klapton you answered some of my questions back whey I was getting my epic in eq 1).
<br />

<br />
Anyway, I gave up eq 1 due to not enjoying the game as much after POP expansion was released, and some burnout from raiding way to much. (one more naked CR and I would have flipped out.)
<br />

<br />
Well darn it, I have tried other games but have found no other that gave me the sheer joy that my bard did in eq1.  (Never forget zooming out from the snowy mountains of the dreadlands and landing on the KC roof.)
<br />
So, here I am wanting to start anew.
<br />

<br />
1. Did they ever give bards in eq2 selo's?  I read they did not and couldnt believe it.  
<br />
Talk about taking the engine off the go kart before you give it to the kid....
<br />

<br />
If they did fix it, does it work like in eq1 with the several variations?
<br />
Fill me in please.
<br />

<br />
2. Troub vs. Dirge, a few older threads here, but the jist I get is...
<br />
Raid Bard = lean toward troubador.
<br />
Solo Bard = lean toward dirge.
<br />
Does this still hold true?
<br />

<br />
My play schedule will pretty much reflect 65 percent small solo sessions, 35 percent longer group and raid sessions.
<br />

<br />
3. Charm/mez, can the troubador use the charmed mob as a pet like in eq1? Does the mez work the same as eq1?
<br />

<br />
4. Fear, can a dirge snare/slow/fear kite like in eq 1?
<br />

<br />
5. skills/songs - do we get skills and songs like in eq1 or is it different.
<br />

<br />
6. Also I have friends who have said I should try the 7 day demo before I buy it to make sure I like it. (I dont this is necessary, but they are adamant that its a different animal than eq1.)
<br />

<br />
Thanks so much for any help, I am anxious to get started.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
						</tr>
					</table></td>
				</tr>
