							<td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
						</tr>
						<tr>
							<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Glad you have positive memories of the EQDiva gang.
<br />
1) Yes.  As of a month ago, a line of Selo's spells has been introduced into the game and these are group speed buffs.  No invis or lev built into them, but the speed is certainly nice.
<br />
2) It is still somewhat true, but the utilty of both classes has improved so that Dirges are certainly assets on raids and Troubs have no problems soloing about as well as a dirge.  They're still different, but both are capable and useful in both roles.
<br />
3) To an extent.  The mez works differently, but you can use it to grab a pet and aim it at another mob and that is a viable tactic.  It is not as powerful or as reliable as it was in EQ1, but then combats tend to be shorter and more forgiving.
<br />
4) Not really.  Fear is short duration and tends to break when mobs take damage.  It is more useful for one-off crowd control than it is for kiting.  But our damage output and debuffs have been buffed enough that I don't miss being able to use fear offensively like I was before the big combat changes.
<br />
5) We get spells and combat abilities, one or more new ones at every level.  They aren't really anything like EQ1 bard songs -- they are really just like other classes spells and abilities.  However most classes pretty much are all spells or all CAs - bards get a nice mix of the two and that really does make the class more flexible and interesting than most other classes.
<br />
6) EQ2 bards are NOT EQ1 bards.  I certainly enjoy playing a Dirge and some of the reasons why I do are similar to the reasons why I liked bards.  By that, I mean it is a busy class with lots to do, has a ton of flexibility in what it brings to a fight, and an enormous bag of tricks for dealing with the unexpected.  But the class and the game in general plays a lot differently from EQ1 -- so it really isn't like being an EQ1 bard at all, though it retains some of the attractive features.  The problem with the 7-day trial is that you really won't get far past generic scout -- levels 1-9 -- in seven days.  You need to get to the mid-late teens to really begin to feel the difference that is bards and to truly experience it, you have to pass 20 and specialize.  I think you SHOULD play the trial, but you have to realize that you aren't going to experience the true depth of the bard class in that 7 days.<br />_________________<br /><img src="http://www.mausturm.com/EQ2/images/dingsig1.jpg"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
						</tr>
					</table></td>
				</tr>
